    <item>
      <title>About me</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/about-me/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/about-me/</guid>
      <description>&lt;nav&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/nav&gt;
&lt;img src=&#34;../../img/boston-mit-round.png&#34; alt=&#34;../../img/boston-mit-round.png&#34; title=&#34;../../img/boston-mit-round.png&#34; width=&#34;40%&#34;/&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/sangwon-hyun/sangwon-hyun.github.io/blob/master/CV.pdf&#34;&gt;CV&lt;/a&gt; / &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/sangwon-hyun/&#34;&gt;Github&lt;/a&gt; / &lt;a href=&#34;https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=LLO62cQAAAAJ&amp;amp;hl=en&#34;&gt;Google Scholar&lt;/a&gt; / &lt;a href=&#34;https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0377-897X&#34;&gt;Orcid&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
I am an Assistant Professor in the &lt;a href=&#34;https://engineering.ucsc.edu/departments/statistics&#34;&gt;Department of Statistics&lt;/a&gt; at the &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.ucsc.edu/&#34;&gt;University of California, Santa Cruz&lt;/a&gt;. Before my current position, I was a post-doctoral researcher (advised by &lt;a href=&#34;http://faculty.marshall.usc.edu/jacob-bien/&#34;&gt;Jacob Bien&lt;/a&gt;), with a Ph.D. from Carnegie Mellon University (advised by &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.andrew.cmu.edu/user/mgsell/&#34;&gt;Max G&amp;#39;Sell&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.stat.cmu.edu/~ryantibs/&#34;&gt;Ryan Tibshirani&lt;/a&gt;) and a B.S. from the University of Michigan.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
I develop statistical tools for large complex data in real-world scientific applications.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
My current research centers around statistically analyzing the ocean&amp;#39;s microbial ecology using high-resolution biological and remote sensing datasets (e.g., flow cytometry, metagenomics, DNA metabarcoding, and spatial proteomics). My research often entails looking at very small things – like single-cell resolution flow cytometry data – to answer very broad questions about ocean ecology, like:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Group</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/group/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/group/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;
I am recruiting for highly motivated postdoctoral scholars, graduate students,
and undergraduate students to join my group!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&#34;outline-container-headline-1&#34; class=&#34;outline-2&#34;&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;headline-1&#34;&gt;
Post-docs
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div id=&#34;outline-text-headline-1&#34; class=&#34;outline-text-2&#34;&gt;
&lt;div id=&#34;outline-container-headline-2&#34; class=&#34;outline-4&#34;&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&#34;headline-2&#34;&gt;
Riddhiman Bhattacharya
&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;div id=&#34;outline-text-headline-2&#34; class=&#34;outline-text-4&#34;&gt;
&lt;img src=&#34;../../img/riddhiman-pic.webp&#34; alt=&#34;../../img/riddhiman-pic.webp&#34; title=&#34;../../img/riddhiman-pic.webp&#34; width=&#34;40%&#34;/&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
Riddhiman’s research interests span the development and application of
statistical methods across multiple disciplines. His past projects have ranged
from modeling resource allocation to studying heart disease. Recently, he has
become deeply interested in marine data, drawn by its richness and its potential
for methodological development. Riddhiman holds a PhD in Statistics from the
University of Minnesota, and brings a strong foundation in both theoretical and
applied statistics to his role at CBIOMES.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
